Exponential Plot for Number of Incidents by Year for Irak and the World.

colors <- c("blue","red","forestgreen","yellow")
plot(colnames(t),t["Iraq",], log="y", type="l", col=colors[1], 
      ylim=c(1, 40000),
      xaxt="n",
      main = "Historical annual number of terrorist attacks in Iraq",
      xlab="Year", ylab="Number of Terrorist Attacks")
## Warning in xy.coords(x, y, xlabel, ylabel, log): 10 y values <= 0 omitted from
## logarithmic plot
lines(rownames(w),w, type="l", col=colors[2])#, pchl
legend("bottomright", # places a legend at the appropriate place c(“Health”,”Defense”), # puts text in the legend
legend=c("World","Iraq"),
  lty=c(1,1), # gives the legend appropriate symbols (lines)
  lwd=c(2.5,2.5),col=colors[2:1]) # gives the legend lines the correct color and width
grid(lty=2)
x_axis = rownames(w)
x_axis = x_axis[1:length(x_axis) %% 2 == 0]
axis(1,x_axis, las=2, cex.axis=.8)

GRAPH 4

Individual Plots of Number of Incidents by Year for Top 10 Countries.

ncountries=10
top<-rownames(tail(x,ncountries)) # top 10 countries by number of terrorist incidents
t<-table(gtd[gtd$country_txt %in% top,c(9,2)])
t<-t[order(rank(rowSums(t))),]
colors <- rainbow(nrow(t))
countries = rownames(t)
#par(pch=22, col="red") # plotting symbol and color 
par(mfrow=c(ncountries/5,5)) # all plots on one page 
for(i in 1:length(countries)){
  plot(colnames(t),t[i,], type="l", col=colors[i],
       ylim=c(1, max(t[,])), 
       xaxt="n",
       xlab="Year", ylab="Number of Terrorist Attacks",main=countries[i])
grid(lty=2)
x_axis = rownames(w)
x_axis = x_axis[1:length(x_axis) %% 9 == 0]
axis(1,x_axis, las=2, cex.axis=.77)
}

Read July 14,2018 European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control COVID-19 Database.

covid<- read.csv("C:/Users/jvpag/R-repository/GTD/COVID19_ECDC_07142020")

 

Table With Number of Terrorist Incidents in 2018 by country.

attacks2018<-table(gtd[gtd$iyear=="2018",c(9)])
num_countries=200
attacks2018<-tail(sort(attacks2018),num_countries)
gtdcountries<-names(attacks2018)
gtdcountries<-gsub(" ", "_",gtdcountries)
gtdcountries[88]<-"United_States_of_America"
names(attacks2018)<-gtdcountries
df<-data.frame(attacks2018)
names(df)=c("country","attacks")

 

Table With Number of COVID Cases and Deaths by country as of 7/14/2020 Incidents in 2018 for Top 10 Countries.

c2018<-covid[covid$countriesAndTerritories %in% gtdcountries,c(7,5,6,10)]
names(c2018)[c(1,4)]<-c("country","population")
covid_cases<-aggregate(cases/1000 ~ country, c2018, sum)
covid_deaths<-aggregate(deaths/1000 ~ country, c2018, sum)
covid_population<-aggregate(population/1000 ~ country, c2018, max)

df1<-merge(df,covid_cases,by="country")
df1<-merge(df1,covid_deaths,by="country")
df1<-merge(df1,covid_population,by="country")
df1

 

GRAPH 5

Terrorist Attacks vs. COVID-19 Cases and Deaths
(Using Top 91 Countries based on Number of Terrorist Attacks in 2018 and COVID-19 Data as of July 14, 2020)

par(mfrow=c(2,2))

fgraph<-function(x,y,titles,ytitle){
    r2<-round(cor.test(x,y)$estimate,2)
    lin.mod <- lm(y~x)
    pr.lm <- predict(lin.mod)
    plot(x, y, "p", las=1, xlab=paste("attacks\nR2=",r2), ylab=ytitle,
         main = paste("Terrorist Attacks vs. COVID-19\n",paste(titles,"(Top ",min(num_countries,91),")")))
    lines(pr.lm~x, col="blue", lwd=2)
}
fgraph(df1$attacks,df1$cases,"Cases","Cases")
fgraph(df1$attacks,df1$deaths,"Deaths","Deaths")
fgraph(df1$attacks/df1$population,df1$cases/df1$population,"Cases Per Capita","Cases")
fgraph(df1$attacks/df1$population,df1$deaths/df1$population,"Deaths Per Capita","Deaths")

 

GRAPH 6

Terrosit Attacks vs. COVID-19 Deaths Per Capita

library(ggrepel)
attacks<-df1$attacks/df1$population
deaths<-df1$deaths/df1$population
ggplot(df1, aes(attacks, deaths, label = df1$country)) +
  geom_text_repel() +
  geom_point(color = 'red') +
  labs(title="Terrorist Attacks vs. COVID-19 Deaths Per Capita")+
  theme_classic(base_size = 16)

 

GRAPH 7

Terrosit Attacks vs. COVID-19 Deaths Per Capita
(For countries with Attacks>10 or Deaths > 10,000)

library(ggrepel)

df2=df1[df1$attacks>10&df1$cases>10,]
rownames(df2) <- 1:nrow(df2)
attacks<-df2$attacks/df2$population
deaths<-df2$deaths/df2$population
ggplot(df2, aes(attacks, deaths, label = df2$country)) +
  geom_text_repel() +
  geom_point(color = 'red') +
  theme_classic(base_size = 16)+
  labs(title="Terrorist Attacks vs. COVID-19 Deaths Per Capita \nCluster Analysis (Attacks>10 and Deaths > 10,000)")+
  geom_segment(aes(x=0, y=0, xend=1500, yend=.0006))
